arch:property.oc:show_val: Short period of sedimentation following abandonment.
5.30 m north south -by- 4.80 m east west.

Locus 9 is a layer of cleaner, lighter soil layer than Locus 8, the dump layer that overlies it. This locus covered the extent of the "hypocaust room" and was just on top of the floor of the room. Very little pottery was found in locus 9 but a number of special finds including a lot of beads were found in the locus. The soil in locus nine was compacted silt and sand with a Munsell color of brown: 7.5yr 5/4. The soil did ball. Most inclusions were small and all were randomly distributed. There was a small amount of charcoal, a medium amount of pottery and a large amount of glass. Charcoal and pottery fragments found were small but glass of all sizes was present. Likely a sedimentation layer.

Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
Brown soil below burn layer (Locus 8) and above the floor in the hypocaust room.
